{"title_page": "Sosnovets, Vologda Oblast", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Sosnovets\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0421\u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0446\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Sokolsky District, Vologda Oblast|Sokolsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|34|N|40|06|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/sokolskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Sosnovets''' ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0446}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Nesterovskoye Rural Settlement, [[Sokolsky District, Vologda Oblast|Sokolsky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 6 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Sokol, Vologda Oblast|Sokol]] is 15&nbsp;km, to Nesterovo is 13&nbsp;km. Pustynya is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Sokolsky District, Vologda Oblast}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Sokolsky District, Vologda Oblast]]\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|official_name          = Sosnovets\n|other_name             = \n|native_name            = \u0421\u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0446\n|nickname               = \n|settlement_type        = Village\n|image_skyline          = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Russia Vologda Oblast#Russia\n|pushpin_label_position = \n|pushpin_mapsize        =\n|pushpin_map_caption    = \n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Russia]]\n|subdivision_type1      = [[List of regions of Russia|Region]] \n|subdivision_name1      = [[Vologda Oblast]]\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Counties of Russia|County]] \n|subdivision_name2      = \n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Russia|District]] \n|subdivision_name3      = [[Sokolsky District, Vologda Oblast|Sokolsky District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = [[List of municipalities of Russia|Municipality]]\n|subdivision_name4      = \n|timezone1              = \n|utc_offset1            = +3:00\n|timezone1_DST          = \n|utc_offset1_DST        = \n|postal_code_type       = \n|postal_code            = \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_footnotes    = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|59|34|N|40|06|E|display=inline}}<ref>[https://mapdata.ru/vologodskaya-oblast/sokolskiy-rayon/ \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u0421\u043e\u043a\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0433\u043e \u0440\u0430\u0439\u043e\u043d\u0430 \u0412\u043e\u043b\u043e\u0433\u043e\u0434\u0441\u043a\u043e\u0439 \u043e\u0431\u043b\u0430\u0441\u0442\u0438]</ref>\n}}\n'''Sosnovets''' ({{lang-ru|\u0421\u043e\u0441\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0435\u0446}}) is a [[types of inhabited localities in Russia|rural locality]] (a [[Village#Russia|village]]) in Nesterovskoye Rural Settlement, [[Sokolsky District, Vologda Oblast|Sokolsky District]], [[Vologda Oblast]], Russia. The population was 6 as of 2002.<ref>\u0414\u0430\u043d\u043d\u044b\u0435 \u043f\u0435\u0440\u0435\u043f\u0438\u0441\u0438 2002 \u0433\u043e\u0434\u0430: \u0442\u0430\u0431\u043b\u0438\u0446\u0430 2\u0421. \u041c.: \u0424\u0435\u0434\u0435\u0440\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0441\u043b\u0443\u0436\u0431\u0430 \u0433\u043e\u0441\u0443\u0434\u0430\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0432\u0435\u043d\u043d\u043e\u0439 \u0441\u0442\u0430\u0442\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u043a\u0438, 2004.</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe distance to [[Sokol, Vologda Oblast|Sokol]] is 15&nbsp;km, to Nesterovo is 13&nbsp;km. Pustynya is the nearest rural locality.\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Rural localities in Sokolsky District, Vologda Oblast}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Rural localities in Vologda Oblast]]\n[[Category:Rural localities in Sokolsky District, Vologda Oblast]]\n\n\n{{VologdaOblast-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Wagino 20100516", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:clean up", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sosnovets,_Vologda_Oblast"}
{"title_page": "Song Car-Tunes", "text_new": "{{short description|Animated film series}}\n{{italic title}}\n''''' Ko-Ko Song Car-Tunes''''', '''''Song Car-Tunes''''', or (some sources erroneously say) '''''Sound Car-Tunes''''', is a series of [[short film|short]] three-minute [[animation]] films produced by [[Max Fleischer]] and [[Dave Fleischer]] between May 1924 and September 1927, pioneering the use of the \"[[Bouncing ball (music)|Follow the Bouncing Ball]]\" device used to lead audiences in theater sing-alongs. The ''Song Car-Tunes'' also pioneered the application of [[sound film]] to animation, four years before [[Paul Terry (cartoonist)|Paul Terry]]'s ''[[Dinner Time (film)|Dinner Time]]'' (released October 14, 1928) and [[Walt Disney]]'s ''[[Steamboat Willie]]'' (released November 18, 1928).\n\n==History==\n\nBetween 45 and 50 ''Song Car-tunes'' were produced and released between 1924 and 1927. The first, ''Come Take a Trip on My Airship'', was released March 9, 1924. Beginning in 1925, an estimated 16 ''Song Car-tunes'' were produced using the [[Phonofilm]] [[sound-on-film]] process developed by [[Lee DeForest]] beginning with ''Come Take a Trip on My Airship''. The remaining 31 titles were released silent, designed to be played with live music in theaters.\n\nThe Fleischer brothers partnered with DeForest, Edwin Miles Fadiman, and Dr. [[Hugo Riesenfeld]] to form Red Seal Pictures Corporation, which owned 36 theaters on the East Coast, extending as far west as [[Cleveland, Ohio]]. In September 1926, the U.S. division of DeForest Phonofilm and Red Seal Pictures Corporation filed for bankruptcy, and the Fleischers ended their use of the Phonofilm system, releasing their last sound ''Song Car-Tune'', ''[[By the Light of the Silvery Moon (song)|By the Light of the Silvery Moon]]'' (1927), just as the [[sound film|sound era]] was about to begin. In early 1929, the Fleischers signed a [[Paramount Pictures]] contract. Former Fleischer partner, Alfred Weiss re-released some of the silent ''Song Car-Tunes'' between 1929 and 1932 with new soundtracks, new animation, and new main titles that exploited the reputation of the popular song films with the elimination of the names of Max and Dave Fleischer.\n\nWith the sound era established, the Fleischers revived the song film series as ''[[Screen Songs]]'' in February 1929 on the strength of being the holders of the original Patent on the concept.  Though [[Ko-Ko the Clown]] had been temporarily retired due to complications with the dissolution of the original [[Inkwell Studios]], the \"Bouncing Ball\" was retained. This new series ran a full seven minutes, with more animation than the early Song Car-Tunes, built around the theme of the featured song.\n\nThe first films in the new series used standards such as ''[[The Sidewalks of New York (cartoon)|The Sidewalks of New York]]'' (released 5 February 1929) and ''[[Old Black Joe]]''. The series continued with new productions of songs previously released in the earlier series, such as ''Daisy Bell'', ''Good Bye, My Lady Love'', ''Mother Pin a Rose On Me'', ''[[Oh! How I Hate to Get Up in the Morning]]'', and ''Come Take a Trip in My Airship'', released by [[Paramount Pictures]] for nine years.\n\nMany of the Screen Songs featured popular stars of stage, radio, and records such as [[Ethel Merman]], [[Rudy Vallee]], [[Lillian Roth]], [[The Mills Brothers]], and the [[Boswell Sisters]]. Starting in 1934, the Screen Songs series focused on the [[big bands]] of the \"Swing Era\", such as [[Abe Lyman]], [[Shep Fields]], [[Gus Arnheim]], [[Hal Kemp]], Jack Denny, [[Vincent Lopez]], [[Henry King (musician)|Henry King]], [[Jay Freeman]], Jerry Baline, Bert Block, Frank Dailey, and [[Jimmy Dorsey]].\n\nThe \"Screen Songs\" concept was revised in a special edition of the [[Technicolor]] ''[[Noveltoons]]'' series in 1945 with ''When G. I. Johnny Comes Home Again'', and the series officially returned in 1947 with ''The Circus Comes to Clown'' and continued until 1951. Paramount attempted to revive the series in 1963 after the television success of ''[[Sing Along With Mitch]]'' with the cartoon ''Hobo's Holiday''.\n\nThe concept of the \"Bouncing Ball\" has become such an established cultural icon, that it has been used in television commercials to sell all sorts of products from sleeping tablets to cat food.  Just before retiring in 1968, Dave Fleischer used a form of the \"Bouncing Ball\" for the ending of ''[[Thoroughly Modern Millie]]'' where he shot cutout animation to \"bounce\" the head of [[Beatrice Lillie]] over the lyrics to the title song.<ref>Pointer, Ray (2016) \"The Art and Inventions of Max Fleischer: American Animation Pioneer,\" McFarland & Co. Publishers</ref>\n\n==List of ''Song Car-Tunes''==\nSee [[Screen Songs]] for sound reissues in [[Cinephone]] and released independently by Alfred Weiss.\n*''[[Alexander's Ragtime Band|Alexander\u2019s Ragtime Band]]'' (1926)\n*''[[Annie Laurie]]'' (1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/A/AnnieLaurie1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[By the Light of the Silvery Moon (song)|By the Light of the Silvery Moon]]'' (August 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/B/ByTheLightOfTheSilvery1926.html SilentEra entry; one of the last of the ''Song Car-Tunes'' releasesd in Phonofilm]</ref>\n*''Come Take a Trip in My Airship'' (1924)\n*''Coming Through the Rye'' (September 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/C/CominThroTheRye1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''Daisy Bell'' (May 1925) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/DaisyBell1925.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[Nelly Gray (song)|Darling Nelly Gray]]'' (February 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/DarlingNellieGray1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[Dixie (song)|Dixie]]'' (November 1925)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/Dixie1925.html SilentEra says this is one of 17 Song Car-Tunes designed for live musical accompaniment in theaters]</ref>\n*''Goodbye My Lady Love'' (June 1924) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/G/GoodByeMyLadyLove1924.html ''Goodbye My Lady Love'' (1924)]</ref>\n*''Has Anyone Here Seen Kelly?'' (March 1926) (sound)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0141146/ 1926 animated version at IMDB]</ref><ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/H/HasAnybodyHereSeenKell1926.html 1926 animated version at SilentEra]</ref>\n*''I Love a Lassie'' (January 1926)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0141281/ IMDB entry]</ref><ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/I/ILoveaLassie1925.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''In the Good Old Summertime'' (1926)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/I/IntheGoodOldSummerTime1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[Margie (song)|Margie]]'' (October 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/M/Margie1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[Mother, Mother, Mother Pin a Rose on Me]]'' (December 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/M/MotherMotherMotherPina1924.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[My Bonnie Lies over the Ocean]]'' (September 1925)\n*''[[My Old Kentucky Home (1926 film)|My Old Kentucky Home]]'' (April 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/M/MyOldKentuckyHome1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''My Wife's Gone to the Country'' (1925) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/M/MyWifesGoneToTheCountr1925.html SilentEra entry]</ref> \n*''Oh! How I Hate to Get Up in the Morning'' (October 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/O/OhHowIHateToGetUpInThe1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[Oh Mabel]]'' (May 1924) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/O/OhMabel1924.html ''Oh Mabel'' at SilentEra]</ref> \n*''Oh Suzanna'' (1925)\n*''Old Black Joe'' (July 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/O/OldBlackJoe1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''Old Pal'' (''Dear Old Pal'') (1925) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/DearOldPal1925.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[Pack Up Your Troubles (1925 film)|Pack Up Your Troubles]]'' (1925)\n*''[[Sailing, Sailing|Sailing Sailing Over the Bounding Main]]'' (1925) \n*''The Sheik of Araby'' (1926) (sound)\n*''[[The Sidewalks of New York (cartoon)|The Sidewalks of New York]]'' (1925) (sound)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0140979 ''The Sidewalks of New York'' (1925) at IMDB]</ref><ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/E/EastSideWestSide1925.html 1925 film at SilentEra]</ref>\n*''[[Swanee River (song)|Swanee River]]'' (1925)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/S/SuwaneeRiver1925.html SilentEra entry; one of 17 silent produced for live musical accompaniment]</ref>\n*''The Old Folks at Home'' (1925) \n*''[[Sweet Adeline (song)|Sweet Adeline]]'' (June 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/S/SweetAdeline1926-2.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[Ta-ra-ra Boom-de-ay|Ta-Ra-Ra-Boom-Dee-Aye]]'' (February 1926).<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0141878/ IMDB entry]</ref><ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/T/TaRaRaBoomDeeAye1925.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[The Trail of the Lonesome Pine (song)|Trail of the Lonesome Pine]]'' (1925)\n*''Toot Toot Tootsie'' (1926)\n*''Tramp, Tramp, Tramp, the Boys Are Marching'' (May 1926) (silent; sound re-issue)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/T/TrampTrampTrampTheBoys1926.html SilentEra entry says originally released silent, may have been reissued 1928 by Weiss Brothers-Artclass Pictures]</ref>\n*''Waiting for the Robert E. Lee'' (1926)\n*''When I Leave This World Behind'' (1926)\n*''When I Lost You'' (1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/W/WhenILostYou1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''When the Midnight Choo-Choo Leaves for Alabam''' (1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/W/WhenTheMidnightChooCho1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''Yak-A-Doola-Hick-A-Doola'' (1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/Y/YakaHulaHickaOoola1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[History of animation]]\n*[[Sound film]]\n*[[Phonofilm]]\n*[[RCA Photophone]]\n\n==Sources==\n*[[Leonard Maltin]], ''Of Mice and Magic: A History of the American Animated Film'' (1980, revised 1987)\n*[[Richard Fleischer]], ''Out of the Inkwell: Max Fleischer and the Animation Revolution'' (2005)\n*[[Ray Pointer]], ''Max Fleischer's Ko-Ko Song Car-tunes (with the Famous Bouncing Ball)'' DVD (2002)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/indexes/earlySoundFilms.html List of Early Sound Films 1894-1929 at Silent Era website]\n\n{{Fleischer Studios}}\n\n[[Category:Film series introduced in 1924]]\n[[Category:Film series disestablished in 1927]]\n[[Category:Animated film series]]\n[[Category:1920s American animated films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:Fleischer Studios series and characters]]\n[[Category:Sing-along]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Animated film series}}\n{{italic title}}\n''''' Ko-Ko Song Car-Tunes''''', '''''Song Car-Tunes''''', or (some sources erroneously say) '''''Sound Car-Tunes''''', is a series of [[short film|short]] three-minute [[animation]] films produced by [[Max Fleischer]] and [[Dave Fleischer]] between May 1924 and September 1927, pioneering the use of the \"[[Bouncing ball (music)|Follow the Bouncing Ball]]\" device used to lead audiences in theater sing-alongs. The ''Song Car-Tunes'' also pioneered the application of [[sound film]] to animation, four years before [[Paul Terry (cartoonist)|Paul Terry]]'s ''[[Dinner Time (film)|Dinner Time]]'' (released October 14, 1928) and [[Walt Disney]]'s ''[[Steamboat Willie]]'' (released November 18, 1928).\n\n==History==\n\nBetween 45 and 50 ''Song Car-tunes'' were produced and released between 1924 and 1927. The first, ''Come Take a Trip on My Airship'' was released March 9, 1924. Beginning in 1925, an estimated 16 ''Song Car-tunes'' were produced using the [[Phonofilm]] [[sound-on-film]] process developed by [[Lee DeForest]] beginning with ''Come Take a Trip on My Airship''. The remaining 31 titles were released silent, designed to be played with live music in theaters.\n\nThe Fleischer brothers partnered with DeForest, Edwin Miles Fadiman, and Dr. [[Hugo Riesenfeld]] to form Red Seal Pictures Corporation, which owned 36 theaters on the East Coast, extending as far west as [[Cleveland, Ohio]]. In September 1926, the U.S. division of DeForest Phonofilm and Red Seal Pictures Corporation filed for bankruptcy, and the Fleischers ended their use of the Phonofilm system, releasing their last sound ''Song Car-Tune'', ''[[By the Light of the Silvery Moon (song)|By the Light of the Silvery Moon]]'' (1927), just as the [[sound film|sound era]] was about to begin. In early 1929, the Fleischers signed a [[Paramount Pictures]] contract. Former Fleischer partner, Alfred Weiss re-released some of the silent ''Song Car-Tunes'' between 1929 and 1932 with new soundtracks, new animation, and new main titles that exploited the reputation of the popular song films with the elimination of the names of Max and Dave Fleischer.\n\nWith the sound era established, the Fleischers revived the song film series as ''[[Screen Songs]]'' in February 1929 on the strength of being the holders of the original Patent on the concept.  Though [[Ko-Ko the Clown]] had been temporarily retired due to complications with the dissolution of the original [[Inkwell Studios]], the \"Bouncing Ball\" was retained. This new series ran a full seven minutes, with more animation than the early Song Car-Tunes, built around the theme of the featured song.\n\nThe first films in the new series used standards such as ''[[The Sidewalks of New York (cartoon)|The Sidewalks of New York]]'' (released 5 February 1929) and ''[[Old Black Joe]]''. The series continued with new productions of songs previously released in the earlier series, such as ''Daisy Bell'', ''Good Bye, My Lady Love'', ''Mother Pin a Rose On Me'', ''[[Oh! How I Hate to Get Up in the Morning]]'', and ''Come Take a Trip in My Airship'', released by [[Paramount Pictures]] for nine years.\n\nMany of the Screen Songs featured popular stars of stage, radio, and records such as [[Ethel Merman]], [[Rudy Vallee]], [[Lillian Roth]], [[The Mills Brothers]], and the [[Boswell Sisters]]. Starting in 1934, the Screen Songs series focused on the [[big bands]] of the \"Swing Era\", such as [[Abe Lyman]], [[Shep Fields]], [[Gus Arnheim]], [[Hal Kemp]], Jack Denny, [[Vincent Lopez]], [[Henry King (musician)|Henry King]], [[Jay Freeman]], Jerry Baline, Bert Block, Frank Dailey, and [[Jimmy Dorsey]].\n\nThe \"Screen Songs\" concept was revised in a special edition of the [[Technicolor]] ''[[Noveltoons]]'' series in 1945 with ''When G. I. Johnny Comes Home Again'', and the series officially returned in 1947 with ''The Circus Comes to Clown'' and continued until 1951. Paramount attempted to revive the series in 1963 after the television success of ''[[Sing Along With Mitch]]'' with the cartoon ''Hobo's Holiday''.\n\nThe concept of the \"Bouncing Ball\" has become such an established cultural icon, that it has been used in television commercials to sell all sorts of products from sleeping tablets to cat food.  Just before retiring in 1968, Dave Fleischer used a form of the \"Bouncing Ball\" for the ending of ''[[Thoroughly Modern Millie]]'' where he shot cutout animation to \"bounce\" the head of [[Beatrice Lillie]] over the lyrics to the title song.<ref>Pointer, Ray (2016) \"The Art and Inventions of Max Fleischer: American Animation Pioneer,\" McFarland & Co. Publishers</ref>\n\n==List of ''Song Car-Tunes''==\nSee [[Screen Songs]] for sound reissues in [[Cinephone]] and released independently by Alfred Weiss.\n*''[[Alexander's Ragtime Band|Alexander\u2019s Ragtime Band]]'' (1926)\n*''[[Annie Laurie]]'' (1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/A/AnnieLaurie1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[By the Light of the Silvery Moon (song)|By the Light of the Silvery Moon]]'' (August 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/B/ByTheLightOfTheSilvery1926.html SilentEra entry; one of the last of the ''Song Car-Tunes'' releasesd in Phonofilm]</ref>\n*''Come Take a Trip in My Airship'' (1924)\n*''Coming Through the Rye'' (September 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/C/CominThroTheRye1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''Daisy Bell'' (May 1925) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/DaisyBell1925.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[Nelly Gray (song)|Darling Nelly Gray]]'' (February 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/DarlingNellieGray1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[Dixie (song)|Dixie]]'' (November 1925)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/D/Dixie1925.html SilentEra says this is one of 17 Song Car-Tunes designed for live musical accompaniment in theaters]</ref>\n*''Goodbye My Lady Love'' (June 1924) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/G/GoodByeMyLadyLove1924.html ''Goodbye My Lady Love'' (1924)]</ref>\n*''Has Anyone Here Seen Kelly?'' (March 1926) (sound)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0141146/ 1926 animated version at IMDB]</ref><ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/H/HasAnybodyHereSeenKell1926.html 1926 animated version at SilentEra]</ref>\n*''I Love a Lassie'' (January 1926)<ref>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0141281/ IMDB entry]</ref><ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/I/ILoveaLassie1925.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''In the Good Old Summertime'' (1926)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/I/IntheGoodOldSummerTime1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[Margie (song)|Margie]]'' (October 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/M/Margie1926.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[Mother, Mother, Mother Pin a Rose on Me]]'' (December 1926) (sound)<ref>[http://www.silentera.com/PSFL/data/M/MotherMotherMotherPina1924.html SilentEra entry]</ref>\n*''[[My Bonnie Lies over the Ocean]]'' (September 1925)\n*''[[M